HEPATITIS - BULGARIA (04)
*************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Wed 27 Sep 2006
From: Brent Barrett <salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
Source: sofiaecho.com, BTA News Agency report [edited]
<http://www.sofiaecho.com/article/first-hepatitis-cases-in-schools-in-bulgarias-plovdiv/id_17860/catid_66>

The first cases of hepatitis A infection were reported in schools and
nurseries in the city of Plovdiv. Most of the cases occurred in the
eastern part of the city, where the mainly Roma-populated Stolipinovo
district is located, the Bulgarian news agency BTA reported. A
hepatitis A epidemics was declared in the neighbourhood but children
underwent immunisation before the start of the school year to prevent
the spread of the infection.
In the eastern part of the city 2 to 6 children in each class were
sick, BTA reported. Some parents decided to stop their children from
attending classes as a preventive measures.
BTA reported that 19 new cases of hepatitis infections were
registered in Stolipinovo overnight. The total number of infected
people reached 710. Another Roma-populated neighbourhood, Sheker
Mahala, was the home of 93 sick people.
A hepatitis outbreak [has also been reported elsewhere] in the
Plovdiv region. The infection occurred in the Roma neighbourhood of
Bogdanitsa village, where 9 people were sick.
--
Brent Barrett
Indianapolis, IN, USA
<salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
[Not auspicious events on the day after it was announced that
Bulgaria would be admitted to the European Union in January 2007,
subject to the fulfillment of strict conditions which include
improvements in food safety. - Mod.CP]
